{"id": "duc04-testb-18:7#21", "contents": "As the impeachment proceedings against President Clinton continued, it became clear that the will of the people meant nothing to the Republicans. Despite the ongoing bombing in Iraq and the growing demand for an alternative to impeachment, Speaker-designate Bob Livingston and his followers remained resolute in their pursuit of impeachment. Even the revelation of Livingston's own adulterous past did not deter him from his goal. The country was divided, and the prospect of a lengthy and bitter Senate trial loomed large. Yet, Livingston and his allies refused to listen to the voices of reason, ignoring the warnings of Democratic leaders like Dick Gephardt and David Bonior, who cautioned against the destructive effects of impeachment."}
